   'No — property alone does not justify deadly force; a life must be threatened',
   'Yes — your post orders authorize force to prevent theft',
   'C',
   'CRITICAL FAIL IF WRONG. Under OCGA 16-3-21, deadly force is only justified to prevent death, great bodily injury, or a forcible felony involving a threat to life. Property recovery never justifies deadly force. This is a non-negotiable disqualifier.',
   true,
   'Deadly Force — Property'),

  ('q-mod02-02', 'MOD-02', 2,
   'Under OCGA 16-3-21, use of deadly force is justified when necessary to prevent which of the following?',
   'Theft of property valued over $5,000',
   'Trespassing on secured premises',
   'Death, great bodily injury, or a forcible felony',
   'Any criminal offense occurring in your post area',
   'C',
   'OCGA 16-3-21 limits justification for deadly force to three conditions: preventing death, preventing great bodily injury, or preventing a forcible felony. All other scenarios fall outside this authorization.',
   true,
   'OCGA 16-3-21'),

  ('q-mod02-03', 'MOD-02', 3,
   'Which of the following best defines a "forcible felony" in the context of OCGA 16-3-21?',
   'Any felony involving property damage over $500',
   'A felony involving the use or threat of physical force against a person',
   'Any offense that requires police response',
   'A felony committed on private property',
   'B',
   'A forcible felony involves actual or threatened physical force against a person — not property offenses. The distinction is critical to lawful use of force decisions.',
   false,
   'Legal Definitions'),

  ('q-mod02-04', 'MOD-02', 4,
   'A subject approaches you aggressively but stops 10 feet away, raises their hands, and says "I''m done." What is your legally correct response under OCGA 16-3-21?',
   'Maintain force posture — verbal compliance may be deceptive',
   'De-escalate and stand down — the immediate threat has ceased',
   'Deploy non-lethal force as a precaution',
   'Detain the subject immediately regardless of compliance',
   'B',
   'When an imminent threat ceases, the legal justification for force also ceases. Continuing to apply force after compliance ends transforms a lawful action into an unlawful one.',
   false,
   'De-escalation'),

  ('q-mod02-05', 'MOD-02', 5,
   'An operator uses deadly force to stop a suspect fleeing with stolen property and claims justification under "protecting the employer''s assets." This action is:',
   'Legally justified under the property protection doctrine',
   'Justified if the employer''s post orders authorize it',
   'Unlawful — property is not a life and does not justify deadly force',
   'Conditionally justified depending on the property''s value',
   'C',
   'No employer post order, company policy, or asset value can override Georgia law. Deadly force to protect property — absent a life threat — is unlawful. Post orders that authorize such force are themselves unlawful.',
   true,
   'Property vs. Life');

